onsensus. In Post-Soviet Social, Stephen Collier examines reform in Russia beyond the Washington Consensus. He turns attention from the noisy battles over stabilization and privatization during the 1990s to subsequent reforms that grapple with the mundane details of pipes, wires, bureaucratic routines, and budgetary formulas that made up the Soviet social state. Drawing on Michel Foucault's lectures from the late 1970s, Post-Soviet Social uses the Russian case to examine neoliberalism as a central form of political rationality in contemporary societies. The book's basic finding--that neoliberal reforms provide a justification for redistribution and social welfare, and may work to preserve the norms and forms of social modernity--lays the groundwork for a critical revision of conventional understandings of these topics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aBiopoliticszRussia (Federation). 0aNeoliberalismzRussia (Federation). 0aPost-communismxEconomic aspectszRussia (Federation). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aBelaya Kalitva.  aPetrine absolutism.  aRodniki.  aRussian absolutist state.  aSoviet Union.  aSoviet cities.  aSoviet city-building.  aSoviet planning.  aSoviet social modernity.  aSoviet social.  aWashington Consensus.  aWindow of Opportunity.  aarchitectural avant-garde.  abudgetary austerity.  abudgetary reform.  abudgets.  abureaucratic structures.  acentralized heating systems.  acity plan.  acity-building.  acollectivity.  acommunal services reform.  aformal rationalization.  agovernment budget.  aindustrial production.  aindustrialization.  ainfrastructural social modernity.  ainfrastructure crisis.  ainfrastructures.  akhoziaistvo.  alabor.  aliberalization.  amarket economy.  amaterial structure.  aneoliberal 